observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the management agreed to:
Constitute the inventory committee to conduct the physical inventory of inventories;
Ensure that the Inventory Committee conduct physical count of inventories semi-annually, and prepare and submit a reconciled Report of Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) to the Auditor.
Ensure that the GSO:
Properly document whenever there is an issuance of inventories to end-users through preparation of Requisition and Issue Slips and Inventory Custodian Slips (for the end-users of semi-expendable properties to establish accountability over the items);
Duly report the result of issuances of inventories to the Accounting Office on a monthly basis, for the recording of expenses;
Maintain stock cards for each type of inventory item;
Ensure the Accounting Office:
Make the necessary adjusting entries and submit the Journal Entry Voucher to the Auditor.
Prepare the reports regularly, such as the SLC (for expendable inventory) and the Semi-Expendable Property Ledger Cards (for semi-expendable inventory), for submission to COA and for semi-annual reconciliation with the RPCI of the Inventory Committee;
Record any issuance of inventories based on the submitted SSMI of the GSO.

We recommended and the Management agreed to ensure that:
The Municipal Accountant prepare the necessary adjusting journal entries to recognize the receivable from AOs as a debit to Due from Officers and Employees and a credit to Cash in Bank effectively presenting the accounts in the books of the LGU;
Collections efforts are made to demand the refund of the amounts due from the previous AOs of the LGU; and,
Prepare the necessary documents as applicable to facilitate the filing of the request for write-off of  unliquidated cash advances - Other Receivables account following the guidelines and procedures outlined in COA Circular No. 2016-005 and its relevant Annexes and request an authority from COA to write-off the dormant receivables following the procedures stated in COA Circular No. 2016-005;

We recommended and the Management agreed to ensure that  for the:
Other Receivables account, prepare the necessary documents as applicable  to facilitate the filing of the request for write-off of  unliquidated cash advances- Other Receivables account following the guidelines and procedures outlined in COA Circular No. 2016-005 and its relevant Annexes and request an authority from COA to write-off the dormant receivables following the procedures stated in COA Circular No. 2016-005;
Advances to Officers and Employees account, Management send a confirmation letter to ICFAU containing all the unliquidated cash advances for their comment on the status of liquidation per their records.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant;
Compute and make necessary adjusting entry to capitalize the borrowing costs to present faithfully the balances of the said accounts. Thereafter, submit a copy of the Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to the Office of the Audit Team for reference.
Disclose the following in the financial statements: the policy adopted for borrowing costs and the amount of borrowing costs capitalized during the year.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor;
Direct and ensure the Municipal Engineer to monitor and implement all projects during the year to ensure the optimum utilization of the 20% Development Fund; and
Strengthen and enhance project planning in the entire LGU, particularly in setting attainable timelines for project implementation to achieve the desired benefits as envisioned in Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2017-1 of DILG and DBM.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Cease and discontinue the practice of consuming fuel for government motor transportation without first undergoing the process of government procurement and disbursement;
Strengthen monitoring of fuel withdrawals and balances to ensure that fuel consumption stays within the contracted amounts/quantities and to easily determine the need to procure additional quantities if needed;
Consider the conduct of EPA for fuel and gasoline so that the operations of the LGU are not hampered due to inadequate supplies at the beginning of the year; and,
Explore alternatives in the supply and management of fuel and gasoline such as the maintenance of gasoline storage tank to service the fuel needs of different government motor vehicles.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor;
Explore strategies in coordination with the HRMO to fill the open plantilla items at the Accounting Office ensuring to hire eligible personnel to augment the Accounting Office workforce;
Instruct and ensure that the Municipal Accountant to submit immediately the transaction documents such as Disbursement Vouchers, Payrolls, Official Receipts, JEVs for adjustments, liquidations, etc. and their corresponding supporting documents, and henceforth, submit it within the reglementary period to ensure their timely evaluation and that deficiencies and/or other observations will be also immediately corrected and/or adjusted.
Direct the Accountant to ensure that personnel in the Accounting Office particularly those involved in the daily recording of transactions in the books of accounts to turnover the receipts and the disbursement records with all paid vouchers and documents evidencing the transactions to the Auditor within ten (10) days from the date of receipt of said documents pursuant to COA Circular No. 95-006 dated May 18, 1995.

Recommendation
We recommended the Management to:
Create a team to conduct an immediate physical count of all its PPE. This committee may be composed of the heads or representatives from the Office of the Municipal Treasurer, the Municipal Accountant, the Municipal Engineer, and a representative from the Office of the Municipal Mayor. They are required to submit the RPCPPE on or before January 31 of each year, copy furnished the COA Auditor concerned pursuant to Section 124 of NGAS Manual, Volume I and Section 490 of GAAM, Volume I;
Further, the committee should be required to check the condition of the property. Any damage, obsolete and unserviceable property shall be reported in the IIRUP and Waste Materials Report and immediately request for disposal. Lastly, the inventory reports should be reconciled with the accounting records to determine the correctness of the property records;
Require each Department Head to conduct every year a physical inventory count of all properties under their office and to submit inventory report to the inventory committee for the random validation of the existence of the property;
Management Comment
Management promised to strategize and exert more efforts to comply with the audit recommendation.
